{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"26671413-0380-495e-805a-a3f5f240e4f0","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Crash reports are saved as `.ips` files in:**\n\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user apps)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system services)\n\n**To find yours quickly:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\nLook for a file matching your process name and recent timestamp.\n\n**You can also use Console.app** → navigate to *Crash Reports* in the sidebar.\n\n**Core dumps** (if enabled) require:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited   # before running the app\n```\n\nThey land in `/cores/` as `core.<pid>`.\n\nThe `.ips` crash log is usually the most useful starting point — it contains the backtrace, signal info, and loaded libraries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a755763d-1511-47c4-b238-b55f8c17c973","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates `.ips` crash reports in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user apps) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-level). These are Apple crash logs.\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, `createdump` is not available (it's a CoreCLR tool). But macOS itself captures crash reports automatically.\n\n\nI'll provide a straightforward answer about where to find these reports and what options are available for debugging NativeAOT crashes on macOS.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"7644:F41F2:E236B9:1097034:69FE925C"},"id":"d16c7dfa-69c6-4b39-a66e-905f3a1f7afb","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:48:22.883Z","parentId":"d486cd4f-281d-4118-baa1-cea3562105b1"}
